{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Intuition: The attention mechanism shifts co-relevant tokens towards each other in the vector space to promote their joint probability of expressing the correct context of the sequence.",
    "Tokens that have the highest weights will drown out those with lower weights indicating that they do not contribute much to contextual meaning, even though they contribute to syntax and grammar.",
    "Word co-occurrence and closeness in embedded space is reminiscent of two key principles in spatial science.",
    "One is from Waldo Tobler, also known as the First Law of Geography, that \"everything is related to everything else, but near things are more related than distant things.\"",
    "The second principle is from the linguist John Rupert Firth that \"You shall know a word by the company it keeps,\" which is a distributional hypothesis (Widdowson, 2007)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The second principle is from the linguist John Rupert Firth that \"You shall know a word by the company it keeps,\" which is a distributional hypothesis (Widdowson, 2007)."
  ]
